body:
I  think the problem here is that the format string itself consists only of ASCII-characters, [and such literals are treated by Jinja as (non-Unicode) `str` instances](http://jinja.pocoo.org/docs/dev/api/#unicode). But calling `.format` with Unicode data [then fails](http://stackoverflow.com/q/3235386/857390).

I can understand the rationale behind using `str` for pure-ASCII string literals, but it would be nice if there was a way to force string literals to Unicode (like Python's `from future import unicode_literals`). The syntax could be similar to that of the [Autoescape extension](http://jinja.pocoo.org/docs/dev/templates/#autoescape-overrides):

```
{% unicodeliterals true %}
    {# All string literals are Unicode literals #}
    {% set foo = "I'm a unicode literal!" %}
{% endunicodeliterals %}

{% unicodeliterals false %}
    {# Standard behavior (type depends on content) #}
    {% set bar = "I'm a str literal!" %}
    {% set baz = "Ünicödë för thë wïn!" %}
{% endunicodeliterals %}
```

As a workaround you can use the [`format` filter](http://stackoverflow.com/a/21828209/857390) instead. However, it seems that it only supports the old (Python 2) string formatting syntax.
